<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJORS; PENALTIES FOR PENA, ROJAS AND 
BRENLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 St. Louis Cardinal second baseman Geronimo Pena, Montreal Expo pitcher Mel 
Rojas and San Francisco Giant coach Bob Brenly were each suspended and fined 
undisclosed amounts by National League President Len Coleman for incidents last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
 Brenly was suspended for 14 games, effective immediately, for charging the 
mound from the bullpen in a July 2 bench-clearing incident that started when 
Rojas hit Barry Bonds with a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
 Rojas was suspended for four games, also effective immediately. 
</P>
<P>
 Pena received a five-game suspension, effective July 14 after the All-Star 
break, for charging the mound and provoking a bench-clearing incident in a June 
30 game against Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Minnesota Twins put designated hitter Dave Winfield, 42, on the 15-day 
disabled list because of a jammed right wrist. Shortstop Pat Meares was 
activated from the disabled list to replace him on the roster. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Chicago Cub broadcaster Harry Caray, 77, was released from the hospital, two 
weeks after he stumbled and fell before a game in Miami. The Hall of Fame 
broadcaster was being treated for an irregular heartbeat discovered after he 
apparently was overcome by heat before the June 23 game at Joe Robbie Stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
